{{Shinto Shrine | Name = Tenjinsha | image = {{image requested|cat=Shiki, Saitama}} | location = [[:en:Saitama Prefecture|Saitama Prefecture]], [[:en:Shiki, Saitama|Shiki, Saitama]], {{ill|Nakasouka|ja|中宗岡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakasouka|qq=}} 1-4-36 | Latitude = 35°50'16.4" N | Longitude = 139°34'56.6" E | Map = | Enshrined deity = {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sugawara no Michizane|qq=}} | type = Village Shrine (村社) | Founded = [[:en:Kan'ei|Kan'ei]] 3 (1626)? | Main Hall = | Other Names = Sōka Tenjinsha (宗岡天神社) | Pilgrimage Sites = | festival = | Rituals = }}
'''Tenjinsha''' (天神社) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] located in [[:en:Shiki, Saitama|Shiki, Saitama]], [[:en:Saitama Prefecture|Saitama Prefecture]].
== History == The shrine is believed to have been founded in 1626 (Kan'ei 3). It is speculated that the {{ill|Kinoshita family|ja|木下氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kinoshita family|qq=}}, former village heads who owned half of the shrine grounds until recently, were involved in its establishment.<ref name="Shrine">Saitama Prefecture Shrine Research Group (Ed.), *Shrines of Saitama: Kita-Adachi, Kodama, Minami-Saitama*, Saitama Prefecture Shrine Association, 1998, pp. 538–539.</ref>
The enshrined deity is {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sugawara no Michizane|qq=}}. While Michizane is typically revered as the "god of learning," at this shrine he is worshiped as the "god of abundant harvests." Reflecting this agricultural connection, the surrounding area includes facilities like the {{ill|JA Asakano|ja|あさか野農業協同組合|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/JA Asakano|qq=}} Shiki Branch and rice shops.<ref name="Shrine"></ref>
== Access == * A 2-minute walk from the Irohabashi bus stop on the local bus route.
== References == {{Reflist}}
== Further Reading == * Saitama Prefecture Shrine Research Group (Ed.), *Shrines of Saitama: Kita-Adachi, Kodama, Minami-Saitama*, Saitama Prefecture Shrine Association, 1998.
